    <!-- WHAT ARE COLLAGEN GUMMIES -->
    <h2 id="what-are">What Are Collagen Gummies?</h2>

    <p>Collagen gummies are chewable supplements that deliver hydrolyzed collagen peptides in a flavored pectin or gelatin matrix. Each serving typically contains 1 to 2.5 grams of collagen sourced from bovine hide, marine fish, chicken sternum, or eggshell membrane. The peptides are pre-broken into small molecular weight fragments (typically 2-5 kilodaltons) so they can be absorbed through the intestinal wall and reach skin, joints, and connective tissue.</p>

    <p>The gummy format has driven explosive growth in the collagen supplement market because it removes the two friction points of traditional collagen powders: the need to mix with liquids and the often-unpleasant taste of unflavored powder. For users who prioritize convenience and consistent daily use over maximum dose, gummies often produce better long-term outcomes than powders that get used inconsistently.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">$2.4B</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the projected size of the <strong>US collagen supplement market by 2026</strong>, growing at over 15% annually. Gummies are the fastest-growing format within this category, driven by their compliance advantages over powders and capsules.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Unlike topical collagen creams — which contain collagen molecules far too large to penetrate the skin — oral collagen gummies work systemically. The amino acids and peptide fragments enter circulation and reach the dermis, joints, and bone matrix from inside the body. This systemic mechanism is why oral collagen produces measurable effects on skin and joints while topical collagen products generally do not.</p>

    <!-- THE 3 TYPES -->
    <h2 id="types">The 3 Types of Collagen in Gummies</h2>

    <p>Not all collagen is the same. The body produces 28 different types of collagen, but only three are clinically relevant to supplementation. Choosing the right type for your goal is the single most important decision in selecting a collagen gummy.</p>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Type I — Skin, Hair, Nails (90% of body collagen)</strong>
        <p><strong>Source:</strong> Bovine hide, marine (fish scales), eggshell membrane. <strong>Best for:</strong> Skin elasticity, wrinkle reduction, hair strength, nail growth. <strong>Effective dose:</strong> 2.5-10g daily of hydrolyzed peptides. The most abundant collagen in the body and the dominant type in skin, tendons, and bone.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Type II — Cartilage and Joints</strong>
        <p><strong>Source:</strong> Chicken sternum (most common), often as undenatured UC-II. <strong>Best for:</strong> Knee pain, cartilage support, joint mobility, osteoarthritis symptoms. <strong>Effective dose:</strong> 40mg daily of UC-II OR 5-10g daily of hydrolyzed Type II. Different mechanism: UC-II works through immune tolerance rather than substrate provision.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Type III — Skin, Vessels, Organs (often paired with Type I)</strong>
        <p><strong>Source:</strong> Bovine hide (almost always co-sourced with Type I). <strong>Best for:</strong> Skin elasticity (synergistic with Type I), vascular tissue, gut lining. <strong>Effective dose:</strong> Same as Type I — typically combined in formulas labeled "Type I &amp; III." Rarely sold alone.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item">
        <strong>Marine vs Bovine vs Chicken</strong>
        <p><strong>Marine:</strong> Higher bioavailability, smaller peptides, sustainable, costlier. <strong>Bovine:</strong> Most studied, balanced cost-effectiveness, the standard in most US gummies. <strong>Chicken:</strong> Almost exclusively Type II for joints. Choose source based on dietary preferences (kosher, halal, fish allergy) and budget.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Vegan "collagen" is a misnomer.</strong> Collagen is exclusively animal-derived. Products marketed as "vegan collagen" contain collagen-boosting nutrients (vitamin C, biotin, silica, amino acids) that support endogenous collagen synthesis but do NOT provide collagen directly. They can be effective for collagen support but should not be confused with actual collagen supplementation.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- BENEFITS -->
    <h2 id="benefits">Clinical Benefits of Collagen Gummies</h2>

    <p>Collagen has accumulated significant clinical evidence over the past decade, particularly for skin and joint applications. These are the four most well-supported benefits, ranked by strength of evidence:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Skin Elasticity &amp; Hydration</strong>
        <p>A 2019 meta-analysis in the Journal of Drugs in Dermatology (11 RCTs, 805 participants) found that 2.5-10g of hydrolyzed collagen daily significantly improved skin elasticity, hydration, and dermal collagen density vs placebo. Effects measurable at 8-12 weeks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Joint Pain &amp; Cartilage Support</strong>
        <p>A 2009 study in International Journal of Medical Sciences showed UC-II at just 40mg daily improved knee pain scores by 40% in osteoarthritis patients vs placebo. Higher-dose hydrolyzed Type I/III also reduces joint pain in athletes and active adults.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Hair &amp; Nail Growth</strong>
        <p>Type I collagen provides amino acids (glycine, proline, hydroxyproline) required for keratin synthesis. Studies show measurable improvements in nail brittleness within 16 weeks. Hair effects are smaller but supported by improved scalp hydration and follicle support.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Bone Density Support</strong>
        <p>Postmenopausal women in a 12-month RCT (2018, Nutrients) showed 7% increase in spine bone mineral density with 5g hydrolyzed collagen daily vs placebo. Mechanism involves osteoblast stimulation and reduced bone resorption markers.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>The 2019 meta-analysis in <em>Journal of Drugs in Dermatology</em> remains the highest-quality evidence to date for oral collagen and skin. <strong>Effect sizes were moderate to large</strong> for skin elasticity (d = 0.72) and hydration (d = 0.66), with no serious adverse events reported across 805 participants and 11 trials.</p>
      <cite>Choi FD et al., 2019 — Meta-analysis of 11 RCTs</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- DOSAGE GUIDE -->
    <h2 id="dosage">Collagen Gummies Dosage Guide</h2>

