    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Collagen Gummies</h2>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What are collagen gummies and how do they work?</summary>
      <p>Collagen gummies are chewable supplements containing hydrolyzed collagen peptides — fragments of the body's most abundant structural protein. After ingestion, the peptides are absorbed through the intestinal wall and circulate to skin, joints, bones, and connective tissue. Effects on skin elasticity and joint comfort typically become measurable after 8-12 weeks of consistent daily use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What types of collagen are in gummies and what do they do?</summary>
      <p>Type I (90% of body collagen) is best for skin, hair, and nails. Type II is specific to cartilage and joint health. Type III often pairs with Type I in skin formulas. Most gummies contain Types I and III together for skin focus, while joint-specific formulas use Type II separately.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How much collagen should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies use 2.5-10g of hydrolyzed collagen per day for skin benefits, with most positive results at 5-10g. For joint support with Type II UC-II, the effective dose is much lower — only 40mg daily. Most gummies provide 1-2.5g per serving, requiring 2-4 gummies daily for skin benefits.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Do collagen gummies actually work for skin?</summary>
      <p>Yes — a 2019 meta-analysis in Journal of Drugs in Dermatology (11 RCTs, 805 participants) found significant improvements in skin elasticity, hydration, and dermal collagen density vs placebo. Results typically measurable after 8-12 weeks of consistent use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Are collagen gummies effective for joints?</summary>
      <p>Yes, but the form matters. Undenatured Type II (UC-II) is the most studied for joint health, with clinical trials showing meaningful reductions in knee pain at 40mg daily. Hydrolyzed Type I/III also has joint benefits but requires higher doses (5-10g daily).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Are there side effects to collagen gummies?</summary>
      <p>Collagen has one of the strongest safety profiles among supplements. Most common side effects are mild digestive symptoms — fullness, mild bloating. Marine-sourced collagen can cause issues for people with fish allergies. Pregnant women should consult a physician before regular use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>When is the best time to take collagen gummies?</summary>
      <p>Timing is less important than consistency. Take collagen gummies any time of day, with or without food. Pairing with vitamin C amplifies effectiveness because vitamin C is a required cofactor for collagen synthesis.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Are vegan collagen gummies real?</summary>
      <p>"Vegan collagen" is technically a misnomer — collagen is animal-derived. Products marketed as "vegan collagen" contain collagen-boosting nutrients (vitamin C, biotin, silica) that support endogenous collagen synthesis but do NOT provide collagen directly.</p>
    </details>

